\chapter{The \texttt{cli.zulip} module and the \texttt{zulip} subcommands}%
\label{cli.zulip}

In this chapter we introduce the subcommands found under [[nytid zulip]],
the [[cli.zulip]] module.
They let us drive a course's Zulip bot---send messages, manage streams and
topics, read unread messages, and run an event-loop bot---directly from
[[nytid]].

\section{Why this lives in nytid, and what it reuses}

Zulip is the team-chat platform we use to communicate with the TAs of a
course.
A bot acts through Zulip's HTTP API using an \emph{API key}, and Zulip issues
a \emph{separate} key per organization.
We run one Zulip organization per course, so the credentials differ from
course to course.
That is the whole reason this belongs in [[nytid]]: [[nytid]] already knows
how to find a course and where that course keeps its data, so it is the
natural place to pick the right Zulip credentials for the course at hand.

We do \emph{not} reimplement any Zulip operations here.
The [[zulipcli]] package\footnote{%
  A sibling literate-programming project by the same author.
} already implements them, and it exposes [[build_embedded_app]] precisely so
that a host program can mount its command set.
Contrast the two ways [[zulipcli]] runs:
\begin{description}
\item[Standalone] the [[zulipcli]] command reads credentials from
  [[~/.zuliprc]], the single zuliprc of the invoking user.
\item[Embedded] mounted inside a host like [[nytid]], it instead reads the
  zuliprc path that the host stores in [[ctx.obj["zuliprc"]]] on the root
  context, before any subcommand runs.
\end{description}
So the only nytid-specific work is to translate a course (and the register it
lives in) into \emph{that course's} zuliprc path, and hand it to
[[zulipcli]] through the context.

\paragraph{Where a course's zuliprc lives.}
We keep a real [[zuliprc]] file in the course's own directory, next to its
[[config.json]] (see \cref{cli.courses}).
This keeps the bot's secret together with the rest of the course's shared
state: a co-teacher who accesses the course through a shared register---or
through the symlinks in the [[mine]] register---gets the same bot identity for
free.
We deliberately do \emph{not} store the API key as a value inside
[[config.json]]: a [[zuliprc]] is the native INI format that [[zulipcli]] and
the underlying [[zulip]] client already expect, so no transformation and no
temporary-file handling of secrets is needed.

\section{Reusing the \texttt{zulipcli} command set}

The module's structure differs from the other command modules in one telling
way.
Elsewhere we write [[cli = typer.Typer(name=...)]] and then add our own
subcommands.
Here the subcommands are not ours, so our [[cli]] \emph{is} the embedded
[[zulipcli]] app; we only rename it and replace its placeholder callback.
<<[[zulip.py]]>>=
"""The nytid zulip command: drive a course's Zulip bot."""

import logging
import pathlib
import typer
import typerconf
from typing import Annotated

from zulipcli.cli import build_embedded_app

from nytid import courses as courseutils
from nytid.courses import registry
from nytid.cli import courses as coursescli

<<constants>>

cli = build_embedded_app(help=<<zulip help text>>)
<<name the embedded app [[zulip]]>>

<<argument and option definitions>>
<<course-selection callback>>
<<helper functions>>

if __name__ == "__main__":
  cli()
@

The auto-discovery in \cref{climodule} registers each module with
[[cli.add_typer(module.cli)]]---without passing a name---so it reads the name
from [[module.cli.info.name]].
The standalone [[build_embedded_app]] leaves that name unset, so we set it
ourselves; this is what makes the command group appear as [[nytid zulip]].
<<name the embedded app [[zulip]]>>=
cli.info.name = "zulip"
@

We can verify the wiring without touching the network: the module must expose
a [[cli]] named [[zulip]] that already carries [[zulipcli]]'s commands.
<<test [[clizulip.py]]>>=
